observations.recommendation:
The GSO-designate coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to obtain records/ information on all PPE items reported in the financial statements, to ensure a complete physical count of all the Municipality’s properties and equipment;
Initiate the disposal of unserviceable properties, in accordance with COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024; and
Commence the necessary procedures required for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts to enable the Municipality to establish reliable PPE balances that are verifiable in terms of existence, condition, and accountability.

We recommended and Management agreed to undertake the following courses of actions:
Establish an M&E System through the issuance of an Executive Order/Administrative Order;
Oblige the M&E Team, through its GFPS, to conduct an assessment and evaluation of all the gender-responsive or GAD-focused policies, programs, projects, accomplishments, and actual costs during your administration;
Task the M&E Team to provide recommendations based on its assessment and evaluation, when necessary; and
Ensure that the M&E Team consolidate the results of the assessment and evaluation in a “GAD Evaluation Report”, which shall be submitted to the DILG Regional Office no later than June of the next term.

We recommended that Management, through the Municipal Accountant;
trace back the old balances forming part of the Due to Pag-IBIG account balance and immediately remit the same to avoid further penalties; and
come up with appropriate measures to ensure that the monthly withheld contributions and loan payments are remitted promptly and accurately.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Trace and determine the reconciling items pertaining to the cash in banks with unreconciled difference totaling ₱5,936,242.33;
Prioritize the preparation and submission of monthly BRS of all cash in bank accounts;
Trace the negative balance of cash in bank accounts in the general and trust fund and provide the Audit Team with the necessary documents;
In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer reconcile the book balances of CIB-LCCA accounts with the cash books; and
Submit the Certificate of Time Deposit and its accompanying bank statement for the CIB-LCTD account.

We recommended that Management:
require the concerned officers/employees with unliquidated cash advances to effect immediate settlement in order to avoid the sanctions imposed under existing laws and regulations specifically under Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code for failure to render account;
immediately send demand letters to the accountable officers especially those that are no longer connected with the LGU;
ensure that all the cash advances granted to LGU personnel shall be liquidated in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002; and
submit additional request for authority from the COA to write-off long dormant receivables that are deemed uncollectible, after all remedies have been exhausted, as prescribed in COA Circular 2016-005.

We recommended that management submit the  following  documents  to
   support the disbursements, otherwise, these shall be disallowed in audit:


     a. Letter of Authority from his/her office;
     b. Memorandum  of  Agreement  stipulating  the  allowances  and  other
        benefits to be granted to the detailed employee;
     c. Daily Time Record and Accomplishment Reports for the period.
